<article>
    <h1>Good move not to repa&#xAD;tri&#xAD;ate for&#xAD;eign con&#xAD;struc&#xAD;tion work&#xAD;ers</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200811/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-11"><time>2020-08-11</time></a>
        - <span>FORUM</span>
        - <span role="byline">Cheng Choon Fei</span>
    </section>

    <p>I ap­plaud the fore­sight of the Gov­ern­ment in iso­lat­ing the for­eign con­struc­tion work­ers for in­ten­sive test­ing in­stead of repa­tri­at­ing them. The strat­egy is bear­ing fruit (S’pore cau­tiously mov­ing towards a new nor­mal,</p>
    <p>Aug 7; and 265,000 for­eign work­ers get nod to re­turn to work, Aug 6).</p>
    <p>This fore­sight may en­able Sin­ga­pore to re­cover faster from the eco­nomic slump be­cause un­like some coun­tries, Sin­ga­pore made the wise de­ci­sion of keep­ing these for­eign work­ers.</p>
    <p>This has saved em­ploy­ers the in­con­ve­nience of hav­ing to re­call work­ers and quar­an­tine each one upon ar­rival, which would in­cur ad­di­tional costs. As it is, con­struc­tion firms are al­ready strug­gling to sur­vive dur­ing this down­turn.</p>
    <p>The strat­egy of test­ing and iso­lat­ing for­eign work­ers could give Sin­ga­pore the edge over other coun­tries by be­ing among the first few to re­cover.</p>


</article>

